<subSubSection pageId="112" pageNumber="113" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="112.[189,324,1194,1220]" box="[189,324,1194,1220]" pageId="112" pageNumber="113">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1194,1220]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1194,1220]" pageId="112" pageNumber="113">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="112.[189,1399,1243,1307]" pageId="112" pageNumber="113">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[644,712,1243,1269]" italics="true" pageId="112" pageNumber="113">vellus</emphasis>
’ meaning ‘cut wool’, referring to the dense pilosity of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="112" pageNumber="113" type="materials_examined">
